I don&#39;t think it can&#39;t.  For example, Atompub uses the accept element.

I think the argument is that this is an advisory value because the resource
may evolve independently of the client (well, this should be expected) and a
client should be able to try the link and see what happens.  Perhaps they
could honor the value (with a fallback):

GET /resource
Accept: application/order+xml; q=0.9, application/order-with-shipping+xml

or they could use it as a last resort, with a hail mary at the end:

GET /resource
Accept: application/order-with-shipping+xml; q=0.5, application/order+xml;
q=0.3, */*

See http://www.w3.org/TR/html401/struct/links.html#adef-type-A for
discussion about using the type attribute in a link element.

-Noah

